<section xml:id="sec-Linear-inequalities" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Linear inequalities </title>
  <activity>
    
    <p>
      Draw the number lines below
    </p>
  
  <image>
    <shortdescription>Number lines</shortdescription>
    <latex-image>
      \begin{tikzpicture}
        \draw[very thick, &lt;-&gt;](-.5,0)--(10.5,0);
        \foreach \x in {0,...,10}{
          \draw(\x,.25)--(\x,-.25) node[below]{\x};
        }
       \draw[-&gt;,black](5.1,.1)--(10,.1);
          \draw(5,.1)circle(5pt);
      \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
  </image>
  </activity>
<activity>
  
    <p>
      Linear inequalities are defined as expressions in which two linear expressions are compared using the inequality symbols. The symbols that are used to represent the linear inequalities are listed below:
    </p>
  
  
  <table>
    <title></title>
  <tabular halign="justify" top="medium" left="medium"  bottom="medium" right="medium">
    
    <row header="yes">
      <cell>Symbol name</cell>
      <cell>Symbol</cell>
      <cell>Example</cell>
    </row>
  
   <row>
      <cell>Less than</cell>
      <cell><m>&lt;</m></cell>
      <cell><m>x+7 &lt;5</m></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell>Greater than</cell>
      <cell><m>x+7 &gt;5</m></cell>
      <cell><m>10x &gt;2 + 16x</m></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell>Less than or equal to</cell>
      <cell><m>\leq</m></cell>
      <cell><m>y\leq 4</m></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell>Greater than or equal to</cell>
      <cell><m>\geq</m></cell>
      <cell><m>-3x \geq 10</m></cell>
    </row>
  </tabular>
  </table>
  
      
    <note>
      <p> The inequality sign always points the smaller number</p>
    </note>
     
    
      
    

  
  
</activity>

<example>
  <p>
    Using inequality symbols, show how each of the following numbers compare.
  </p>
  <tabular>
    <row  halign="center">
      <cell>(a) 2 and 5</cell>
      <cell>(b) 7 and 5</cell>
      
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell>Solution</cell>
      <cell />
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell>(a) 2 is less than 5</cell>
      <cell>(b) 7 is greater than 5</cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell>(a) The symbol used should be 2&lt;5</cell>
      <cell>(b) The sybol used should be 7&gt;5</cell>
    </row>
    
  </tabular>
</example>

<subsection xml:id="subsec-representation-of-simple-inequalities">
  <title>REPRESENTATION OF SIMPLE INEQUALITIES</title>
  <p>
    Inequalities can be represented in a number line.
  </p>
  <p>
    To plot an inequality such as <m>x&gt;3</m> on a number line, first draw a circle over the number (e.g.,3). 
    Then if the sign includes equal to <m>(\geq or \leq)</m>,
     fill in the circle. If the sign does not include equal to <m>(&gt; or &lt;)</m>,
     leave the circle unfilled in. Finally, draw a line going from the circle in the direction of the numbers that make the inequality true.
  </p>
  <image>
    <shortdescription>Number line</shortdescription>
    <latex-image>
      \begin{tikzpicture}
        \draw(0,0)--(11.5,0);
        \foreach \x in {0,...,11}{
          \draw(\x,.25)--(\x,-.25) node[below]{\x};
        }
        \draw[-&gt;,black,very thick](3.2,.5)--(11,.5);
          \draw[very thick](3,.5)circle(5pt);
        

      \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
  </image>
</subsection>

<example>
  <p>
    Represent each of the following inequalities in a number line.
  </p>
  <p>
    (a) <m>x \leq 8</m>
  </p>
  <p>
    (b) <m>x &gt; 8</m>
  </p>
  

    <p>
    (a) <m>x \leq 8</m> means <m>x</m> is less yhan or equal to 8. It is represented as shown.
  </p>

 
  
  <image>
    <shortdescription>Number lines</shortdescription>
    <latex-image>
      \begin{tikzpicture}
        \draw(0,0)--(11.5,0);
        \foreach \x in {0,...,11}{
          \draw(\x,.25)--(\x,-.25) node[below]{\x};
        }
       \draw[very thick,&lt;-](.3,.5)--(8,.5);
          \draw[very thick,fill=black](8,.5)circle(5pt);
      \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
  </image>

  <p>
  Notice that the circle is filled to show that 8 is included in the inequality.
   
</p>
<p>
  (b) <m>x&gt;5</m> means <m>x</m> is greater than 5. It is represented as shown
</p>
  
  <image>
    <shortdescription>Number lines</shortdescription>
    <latex-image>
      \begin{tikzpicture}
        \draw(0,0)--(11.5,0);
        \foreach \x in {0,...,11}{
          \draw(\x,.25)--(\x,-.25) node[below]{\x};
        }
       \draw[very thick,-&gt;](5.2,.5)--(11.1,.5);
          \draw[very thick](5,.5)circle(5pt);
      \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
  </image>


</example>






  
  
